title: Roku Soundbridge M2000 replacement end cap

description.text:
Designed this for a friend to replace his Roku M2000 endcaps, which had broken their tabs so the endcaps would fall out.  These are not an identical match to the originals as there is no curve on the flat LCD side.  The M2000 has been out of production for awhile.  They fit tightly and don't use tabs to stay in.  
UPDATE:  updated stl just a little.  Flange inside one portion was a fraction of mm too long.
Print at 0.15 layer ht and 20% infill and 3 perimeters w PLA seemed to fit fine.

comments.text: I posted your thing on the Roku forums. You may have some requests for the smaller caps from the M500/M1000 series. I see a lot of M1000s on eBay and they are all missing their end caps :D

This object was designed as a study in preassembled interconnecting objects. This is my second attempt - the first fused together in printing. To avoid the need for supports, which would immobilize the ball joint, there are ten tiny support cylinders between the two cubes. These supports aren't perfect, so the bottom surface of the upper cube won't print beautifully, but it did a whole lot better than I expected. I intend to create an OpenSCAD script for a parameterized version this object, so watch this space if you're interested. If you have any thoughts on modifying the design to print horizontally (so that many more can be attached!), please leave a comment. Yes, I do realize that the geometry is not super clean. I modeled this in Blender when I should have used OpenSCAD. That said, it could be a whole lot worse, and the file is still nice and tiny. Thanks for looking!

The initial build was set to 20% infill with 2 shells and a layer height of 0.2mm. I scaled the cubes down to 30mm square because I was concerned that the build would fail. It worked out fine and will probably work at its original size as well.  
The support cylinders closest to the corners can be easily removed with needle nose pliers. Once those are pulled out, the supports near the center will break free with just a little torque.  
Enjoy!

description.text:

3D Printable Paul is designed for the hobbyist user and is optimised for printing on a desktop printer. Feel free, however, to print a life size version if you have a big enough machine.

  • HUNG OVER:
    Overhanging parts, or anything that extends greater than 45 degrees will require support material to be generated. Most 3D printing software will generate the required supports and the algorithms that create those supports are constantly improving. If you watch the time-lapse of the print we’ve done you can see the supports that are built to hold Paul’s hands; these are a good example of overhangs.

  • SHE SHELLS SEE SHELLS:
    Each printer software will allow you to adjust the machine to optimise your print. One factor of printing in 3D is the number of shells that the user chooses to generate. The more shells generated, typically the stronger the part is but the less detail and versa vice. So if you want the buttons on Paul’s jacket to show up better, limit the number of shells to about 2. If you want to make it a 'Super Paul', increase the shells accordingly.

  • THE BLACK AVENGER OF THE SPANISH MAIN:
    One way that 3D Printing works is to build a raft out of the material your machine uses and then print your part on top of that. Unlike Tom Sawyer and his adventures on the Mississippi, a raft is something to be avoided. This design benefits from having its own stand and provided your machine has a very flat and level build plate you will have little trouble printing a copy of Paul for yourself. (In the future designing and printing parts while avoiding the need for rafts will ensure trouble-free printing.)

  • ON THE LEVEL:
    The last and most important trick in getting the best out of your desktop printer is to make sure the surface you are printing on is level. With many types of desktop printers there are three screws underneath the build platform that allow you to adjust the level. The printers themselves have a method for calibrating the build platform level, but maybe the best way of making sure is to adjust while it’s printing. A good leveling file is this one:
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39430/#files
    It’s the Bed_Levelling_2.stl file that ensures that your next build comes out brilliantly.

title: A Better Glass Clip... With a BONUS

description.text:
Like most who use a glass plate to print, I was using spring steel paper clips.  They work great until the extruder head gets close to the edge of the build platform.  When that happens, duck.  Spring clips start flying and once, the head draged the clip, the glass and the build completely out of the machine, where if fell to the floor.  
The other day, I was cleaning up shop and came across a drawer full of clips designed to hold sockets to steel strips (pic 1).

After eyeballing the clips and the glass on top of my aluminum build plate, I took a pair of pliers and carefully bent one of the clip's ends to about 80Âº (pics 2 & 3). These things are hardened, so care must be taken, otherwise they will snap. Heating them may help remove some of the temper, but you don't want them to lose their spring. The clip slid neatly onto the build plate from underneath, around the edge and onto the surface of the glass (pics 4 & 5). Now my glass plate is held securely with nothing sticking up to grab an errant extruder nozzle. About that bonus... Now, when I went to publish this, the default "You need to publish something that isn't an image" message appeared, so I went through my stuff, and if you're a gearhead, here's something for you... A spark plug wire separator, known as a "comb". As you can see, I've gone a little overboard on my own ride, but here's the basic comb. It'll work on both 4 and 8 cylinder cars. Enjoy. PROOF OF CONCEPT:
Whenever I'm planning on a trip, I print out bunches of my favorite puzzle as give-aways (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:27022). People always like getting something for nothing and I enjoy making that happen. I print 24 at a time, and my first print of the night was slightly off-center, putting one of the pieces directly on top of one of my glass clips. The final three photos show the results. The part printed fine with only a small indentation outlining the shape of the clip. Proof this clip works for me.

description.text:
Adapters to convert a geared 28BYJ-48 to a cheap and light direct drive stepper.
There are stl files that allow you to use the original mounting style or convert to a nema 14 mount.
As you would expect from its size and weight, this motor is suitable for very light duty only.
Read the instructions for some important considerations before making this.

If you print this in PLA be very sure to watch the heat. The motor could easily get hot enough to soften the plastic. These motors seem to vary somewhat in their construction so I won't discuss disassembly and you may have to make some modifications to the drive shaft and possibly the adapter. You can customize the scad file to generate either type of mount. You can also specify the size of bearing you are using. I used two MR105ZZ bearing stacked together to give better side force resistance. If you want a standard shaft you can use pretty much any 5mm id bearing(s). The bearings are intentionally a tight fit and have to be pressed into place. You might have to adjust the clearance for your printer. Since I am using PLA, I drilled holes in the case and used screws to retain the adapter; but I would recommend a higher temperature plastic that you could glue in place. I recommend that you also cut the connection as shown in the pictures to convert the motor to bipolar operation as described by:
http://www.jangeox.be/2013/10/change-unipolar-28byj-48-to-bipolar.html Of course you have to use a different driver if you choose to do this. The shaft is bored to have a tight fit over the original driving gear. It is attached with epoxy. This works even though the gear is nylon because it fills the space between the gear teeth. I extended the epoxy down the nylon shaft and on to the rotor to reinforce it. Be careful not to get any epoxy where it will interfere with free rotation.
I have included a stl for the shaft, but I made a metal version. I think it would be rather difficult to get a printed version to work. It might be possible to use tubing.

description.text:
This part was designed by myself to fit a Trail Tech Vapor along with the stock Suzuki ignition switch and indicator lights as close to the 1-1/8" handlebars as possible. Unlike other mounts that have been produced out of laser or water-cut metal, this mount attaches directly to the handlebar and protects/hides the wires. The design uses the stock Trail Tech countersunk fasteners for mounting the Vapor to the bracket and M4 nuts and bolts for clamping the bracket to the bar. I strongly recommend using a moderate thread-lock on all the fasteners as the bike will vibrate everything loose sooner than you might think. Currently on the 3rd iteration. This clamp might fit other bikes, like the DR 650. It was designed to clear Pro-Taper bar mounts with a minimum 70mm spacing between them.
Please contact me if you want a tweaked version for your bike. Will be adding a new version for the Trail Tech Voyager as soon as that arrives. If you like the design, please "like" the design and post pictures of your completed copy.

Printed in PLA on a lightly modified Ultimaker at 100 micron layer height, .4mm nozzle, and a heated bed @70C. Wall thickness is set to .8mm with an extra 1.2mm on the top and bottom layers. It is plenty strong with 15% infill, anything over 25% just seems silly. If you're worried about strength and being able to really clamp it down hard, I'd increase the wall thickness a bit, but the skirt around the front hiding the wires is still only going to be two layers thick.
Make sure to print these flat side down (the arch for the bar should be up).

A simple organizer for the GoPro HERO4 dual-battery charging station with slots for additional batteries and SD cards.  The floor of each slot is raised so that the equipment height is even across the top.  The battery charger can be used while stored and the cutout for the USB jack is over-sized to allow for most cables.

My print was done at 300 microns in ABS, support material in place for the USB cutout, three perimeter layers, four upper and lower surface layers, and 15% infill.  
The slots for the batteries and SD cards were sized very slightly larger than necessary (0.5mm) to insure that they would not be too tight when the print cooled and contracted.  When flipped over, the SD cards will fall out, but the batteries and charger are just snug enough to stick.

description.text: I coprocessed two servo motors hooked up to an arduino to get it to drive off the build plate. See the video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3zP-1TUq0ss&feature=youtu.be Read more about it here: https://wordpress.com/post/84694066/137/

Before your print, place the smaller 180 degree servo horns onto your standard size servo motors. (I used these full rotation servo motors from sparkfun: https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9347) Mid print, place two standard size servos into your print, with the servo horns attached, right before it starts to print the top section of the piece. Make sure the "ends" of the horns are tangent to the top and bottom of the servos. I designed the wheels for that orientation, to make coprocessing simple. The overhang in the part will now be supported by the servo motors. To get the filament to stick well, I laid down a strip of painter's tape. After the print has finished, plug the arduino into your computer, with whatever motion behavior you want to control the servos. The wheels will break the build adhesion and your part can drive off the build plate.

title: New frame for Sunhokey for 11x11x9 build.

description.text: A new frame for Sunhokey printer to increase build size to 11x11x9 inches.

Buy Sunhokey acrylic 3D printer.  Print these parts.  Build a 11.5 inch by 12.5 inch heat bed and buy 4 M8 nuts and about fifty m3-12 screws and m3 nuts.  Sunhokey printer includes enough T2.5 belt for this, but if you already cut it, you'll need to buy more belt.  
To make MKS Gen-2Z V1.1 board work with two extruders, cut the traces from the Z2 dir and Z2 step  pins to RPK4_M2.  Then wire the Z2 dir and Z2 step pins to pins 5 and 7 in AUX-1 as in the photograph.  Then modify Z_STEP_PIN=26, Z_DIR_PIN=28, Z_ENABLE_PIN=24, E0_STEP_PIN=46, E0_DIR_PIN=48, E0_ENABLE_PIN=62, E1_STEP_PIN=57, E1_DIR_PIN=58, E1_ENABLE_PIN=62 in pins.h in Marlin.  Plug your extruder 0 into Z1 and extruder 1 into Z2.  Wire your two Z motors in series and plug them into E0.  If you probably don't have to modify the dir pin because Marlin probably doesn't ever run the two extruders in opposite directions.  But I haven't tested it that way.
Print the various parts listed in parts.scad.  Comment/uncomment the various parts and compile parts.scad and print.

comments.text: Just make the bed out of a piece of wood.  Wood doesn't melt.  Drill holes in the wood as indicated on the bed template.  You can chop up the template and only print parts of it for the various holes.  Or you can just eyeball the holes.  I doubt your acrylic X holder is compatible. All over the place, there are holes for M3 screws.  Some of them are bigger than others.  A screw goes through the bigger ones and a nut goes on the screw.  Screws tap into the smaller ones without a nut.
